==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*halðan'' ‘to watch, look after’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[halda]], Old Saxon [[haldan]] (Dutch [[houden]]), Old High German [[haltan]] (German [[halten]]), Old Norse [[halda]] (Swedish [[hålla]]), Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐌻𐌳𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'hæaldan/}}

===Verb===
'''healdan''' (class VII strong: '''hielt''' ‘he holds’, {{Unicode|'''hēold'''}} ‘he held’, {{Unicode|'''hēoldon'''}} ‘they held’, ('''ġe''')'''healden''' past participle)
# to keep watch over (cattle etc.)
# to [[hold]] fast, to [[grasp]]
# to [[contain]]
# to [[possess]]
# ''(intransitive)'' to maintain one’s position against an enemy

